This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Lin Hehuang, southern weekend staff writer

Editor in chief | Suping Ma

"Mom, you are waiting for me outside, it is easy to cross-infection when you enter the hospital. " On the morning of the New Year's Eve, to comfort my mother, I tightened the mask on my face and walked into the People's Hospital in my hometown of the county seat against the cold wind, cOVID-19 is also one of the designated hospitals in Zhejiang Province for the diagnosis and treatment of pneumonia.

The staff at the Registration Desk wore the same blue medical mask as mine. Behind the black frame were a pair of young eyes. They asked me "what department should I go to? ". I took a breath and said the sentence in my mind repeated practice for a long time, "hello, I have been to Wuhan, I want to do an examination. ".

1
Tough call

1

###Tough call

It was a difficult decision.

At the end of 2019, there was an outbreak of "pneumonia of unknown cause" in Wuhan. At that time, I was on a business trip in Wuhan, and had passed by the South China Seafood Market, which later caused a storm in the city. I did not expect that about 20 days later, the so-called "unexplained pneumonia" will be included in category B infectious diseases, and according to plague, cholera, two category A infectious diseases management.

Seventeen years ago, when I was learning to add, subtract, multiply, and divide, I didn't really experience an outbreak of infectious disease. There were too many safeguards in place. Although I bought an N95 mask before I left for work, I didn't take it off until I got back to my hotel in the evening. The gloves I bought in advance were too big to completely block my hands from the outside world, and I didn't wear a hat.

On January 26,2020, the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) disclosed that there were several wildlife trading shops in the West district of the south China Seafood Market, where a relatively high number of samples tested positive for COVID-19 nucleic acids were found. And I've been there.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Xinhua News Agency / Photo)

I left Wuhan on January 4th when my work was over.

Watching the news, I observed that the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission had always stated in its announcement before January 11 that "no obvious evidence of human-to-human transmission has been found, and no medical staff infection has been found" , and only reminded citizens to wear masks when necessary, if you have fever, respiratory tract infection symptoms, especially persistent fever, timely to medical institutions. The notice did not mention what kinds of people would need to be self-observed and segregated from their homes.

I was so scared to hear about common pneumonia that I watched my body temperature closely every day for a week after returning from Wuhan. I didn't go out for any special circumstances, and I mostly cooked meals at home.

Wuhan Health Commission did not report any new cases for six consecutive days from May 5 to 11. The number of cases remained at 41 in the announcement issued from May 11 to 16. Most of the severe and dead patients were middle-aged and elderly people with serious underlying diseases. I was relieved, like most people, that this matter has been over, and into the annual summary of the work before the Spring Festival.

However, since the 13th I have developed symptoms of fever. The night I took the antipyretic, I sweated all over, but the next day my temperature returned to normal from 38 degrees, with only minor symptoms of nasal congestion and cough, and no suspicious symptoms of chest tightness, shortness of breath, and repeated fevers. In the meantime, I stayed at home and took my armpit temperature every hour.

No one could have predicted that since January 19, the COVID-19 has been like a Pandora's box that has been opened. From the initial "preventable and controllable" to the thousands of confirmed deaths, the country has launched a level 1 response, with the exception of Tibet.

On January 23, when only 27 cases were confirmed in Zhejiang Province, where my family lived, the first alarm went off across the country, with some relatives and friends questioning whether the province had "gone too far. ".

By then, I was back at home in Zhejiang, with nothing wrong except an occasional cough. When I got home, I wore a mask to protect myself from possible cross infection. I never left the house. The closest I ever got to my parents was a hug from my worried mother before going to the hospital.

Everybody was getting scared. I was getting scared.

2
An Hour's wait, an unsolved murder

2

###An Hour's wait, an unsolved murder

On January 22, Hubei Province, with more than 200 confirmed cases, launched a level II public health emergency response. On the same day, the home of the pneumonia prevention and Control Work Leading Group issued a notice, "nearly 20 days in Wuhan travel or residence history, or with Wuhan personnel have close contact" personnel do not panic, please contact the hospital.

20 days, in fact, more than the incubation period of the pneumonia 14 days, but it coincides with the date of my business trip in Wuhan. Although I did not feel any discomfort, but for the health and safety of my family, I decided to go to the hospital for a check-up.

New Year's Eve, the hospital is no longer crowded. The staff at the registration desk was very calm and did not pause for my statement. They methodically recorded my name, age, home address and mobile phone number in the medical record book and helped me hang up the number of the fever clinic, and gave me a sign to go to the triage table.

The nurse at the triage desk was a little flustered when she heard that I had been to Wuhan. The little hot water bottle changed from left hand to right hand, and from right hand to left hand. She could not look me in the eye. After a nurse took my temperature and recorded it, another "heavily armed" paramedic appeared in front of me, directing my "suspect" to the fever clinic.

The so-called "fever clinic" is not set up in the General Clinic Building of a department, but the clinic building space on a low board room. The atmosphere here is markedly more serious than in the clinic. Each doctor was wearing a blue protective suit, and I and an older brother who had just returned to Zhejiang from Xiantao, Hubei Province, were given a surgical mask and helmet. I did not think at the time, this protective cap will accompany me through New Year's Eve, until the fourth day of the New Year to take off.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Setting up of fever clinic. (photo / photo by Lin he-huang)

The Wuhan contact history is a very important part of the doctor's routine inquiry. I took out my cell phone and opened up the detailed travel history I had compiled from the previous night's insomnia until 2 am. I told my doctor one by one in chronological order, adding, "Is there anything else you want to know? " The doctor, who was busy writing, raised his head and gave me a strange look.

"The family member contact way gives me. " I give mother's contact way to her. I didn't think the epidemic would get so bad in Wuhan. I didn't tell my parents that I had been to Wuhan on business. Now, they need to hear from the doctor how worried and frightened they must be to know that my daughter had recently been to the city that dominated the headlines.

After taking a blood vessel, I was directed to a bus opposite the boarding house for a chest x-ray. The results of the blood test and the chest film will take an hour to come out. Next to the elder brother Xiantao, who was clearly in a bit of a panic, repeatedly said that he had just taken a train from Xiantao's hometown to Wuchang and returned to Zhejiang, but had not stopped in Wuhan, i've got work to do.

The hour of waiting for the result was long and desperate. To be honest, I don't feel like I'm infected -- I've already passed the 14 day incubation period, and I don't have any obvious suspicious symptoms like fever. But I did have a fever after I left Wuhan. Could it be that you were infected, and that your young, strong immune system beat the virus? Will this have a lasting effect on my lungs and other organs?

In great anxiety, I waited for a piece of good news and not so bad news.

The good news is, my blood work is clear, my chest x-rays are clear, there's no ground-glass opacity, and it doesn't match the infection.

Not Bad news is, I and Xiantao big brother's "suspicion" is still not lifted, the doctor advised us to be admitted to the isolation ward for further examination and diagnosis.

3
The lucky one with the kit

3

###The lucky one with the kit

I was shocked to hear that I had been in good health and had never been hospitalized before.

On the other side, waiting outside the hospital, my mother knew that I had been to Wuhan -- as if I were a "suspicious person" -- and that people in the small town were either neighbors or fellow students and colleagues, old relationships break down walls of impermeable information.

When friends in the health and government systems got the news, they called their families to find out about me and tried to inform them of the follow-up arrangements. The family learned that the county had no confirmed cases, not even a suspected case, and that the county had done a lot of preparation for the epidemic. One doctor also said that people like me who don't have a fever at the moment have a low risk of infection, so parents shouldn't worry too much.

The quarantine ward was set aside specifically for this outbreak. The doctors were armed to the teeth with gloves, shoe covers and goggles, and the smell of alcohol wafted over them as they approached.

After being admitted to the isolation ward, several waves of doctors arrived in a row, from the county hospital to the county CDC. Tight-fitting protective clothing dressed them in sweat, even goggles are covered with a thin layer of water droplets. I told my story over and over again, and every single one of the medical staff who came in kept a running tally.

A medical staff took out two about 20 cm long cotton swabs, told me to nose into the secretion, "both nostrils. ". He also gave me a cylinder of transparent small box, let me "deep spit" in the inside, "preferably deep phlegm. Spit in front of other people? I say no in my heart, but I have to do what I'm told. I later learned that it was to take my sample for a test kit.

There was no Wi-Fi or TV in the isolation room, and I charged my phone with five gigabytes of data, spinning my brain with messages and rumors. Impressively, a report in people magazine noted that the kit was under pressure in all aspects of production, procurement and transport, and that it was difficult to confirm the diagnosis.

This Day is New Year's Eve, my mother specially found a brand-new blue insulated box, the New Year's Eve dinner to me outside the isolation ward building. The nurse reminded her that meals sent to the isolation ward were best placed in disposable containers.

The sound of firecrackers easily penetrated the soundless room outside the window. I opened wechat and the parents'video, showed them the fabled isolation ward and told them that I had taken my temperature three times and had no fever. I also turned on the live broadcast of the Spring Festival gala on my mobile phone, the bright colors of the stage contrasted with the blue and white stripes on hospital bed sheets.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Mother brought me New Year's Eve dinner in a thermos bucket. (Lin Hehuang Photo / photo)

The hospital schedule always seems to be an hour or two ahead of the rest of the world. Before 11 o'clock, the nurse came to remind me to go to bed. Before I could say "happy New Year" to her, she was busy going to the next ward. I turned off the lights and lay down on the slightly firm bed until I saw Jackson Yi twist his waist on stage for the gala and fell asleep contentedly.

Around 2:30 pm the next day, my family called to tell me that my kit came back negative, as if I wasn't COVID-19, it was 9:30 p.m. by the time the paramedics reached me from the top floor to the bottom.

The lifting heart finally fell more than half.

4
Waiting to be discharged

4

###Waiting to be discharged

According to the National Health Council announced the diagnosis and treatment plan, two consecutive negative nucleic acid testing (sampling time interval at least one day) , to be released from isolation.

The next day, a doctor who visited the ward said that after the results of the first kit came out, it was 48 hours before the second nucleic acid kit could be tested, and the county's testing capacity was limited, all samples collected in this county will be sent to the city CDC unified testing, if the number of samples sent to the test will be a little later out, "generally 2-5 hours can know the results. ".

A nurse on duty in an isolation ward said the interval between the two kits was always "variable" and let me have a good rest.

In what was supposed to be a 48 hour family reunion, I took dozens of tests, including blood pressure, a urine routine, and a Procalcitonin test. I took a flu pill of Oseltamivir every morning and night, there is an indwelling needle in the vein of my left forearm for the doctor to draw blood and give me fluids. Every time he inhales, the needle seems to cool through the skin.

After the negative screening results came out, my physical condition is good, no more infusion, the nurse every two hours or so to visit me. From them, I also learned that although the county hospital's epidemic prevention materials are not adequate, but the current reserve situation is also acceptable, "no Hangzhou and Ningbo tension. ".

The nurses on duty were multitaskers, and I often heard them scurrying in the hallways. In addition to the routine check of the ward and the temperature of the infusion, the nurse is also responsible for comforting the patient when the patient is unstable and shouting to be discharged.

Accustomed to the Hustle and bustle of the city, I felt the night in the isolation ward was too quiet. I could only hear the occasional cough next door and the pitter-patter of rain outside the window.

Forty eight hours later, a second nucleic acid test arrived, only this time I waited much longer for the results than the first.

At around 4 p.m. on January 26, I had worn the same cap for three days, covering my increasingly greasy hair. A medical worker brought a long cotton swab and "spit box" . Unlike the first test, the Swab is used to extract secretions from the back of my throat, and these samples will be sent to the city for testing.

A friend in the health system told me that the number of samples needed to be tested in the city had skyrocketed over the past two days, that the lab responsible for nucleic acid testing had been working around the clock, and that my samples were in line for testing. At about 9 a.m. on January 28, I was told that the second test was negative and that I could be discharged, but that I would have to stay at home for another week.

When I got home, my family told me that despite the efforts of the community, the hospital and the county to protect the privacy of the quarantined patients, a neighbor knew, and she "reminded" US that we could only use the stairs to get up and down the stairs, and quickly my personal information and my house number to inform the property, but also "tell" she knows people, the community I have such a "suspicious person.

The property had little knowledge of the difference between a confirmed diagnosis, a probable diagnosis and a medical observer, and spread false information about me around. At one point, my family car was not even allowed into the garage, it was explained in a roundabout way that it was because "when it rains, you don't want the rain to get into the garage" . However, when 2019 Typhoon Lekima brought heavy rain to Zhejiang, none of the communities had such regulations.

At that moment, clearly not infected with the virus I feel that they almost became the hometown of the "sinner. ".
